90. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Ovid MEDLINE(R) <2019>
ID  - 31304823
T1  - Differential insulin response to oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) in overweight/obese polycystic ovary syndrome patients undergoing to myo-inositol (MYO), alpha lipoic acid (ALA), or combination of both.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/09513590.2019.1640200
A1  - Genazzani, Alessandro D
A1  - Prati, Alessia
A1  - Marchini, Federico
A1  - Petrillo, Tabatha
A1  - Napolitano, Antonella
A1  - Simoncini, Tommaso
Y1  - 2019//
Y2  - 20190713//
N2  - Polycystic ovary syndrome is characterized by several endocrine impairments, insulin resistance and hyperinsulinemia. We aimed to evaluate the effects of myo-inositol (MYO), alpha-lipoic acid (ALA) and a combination of both. Setting : retrospective study. Ninety overweight/obese patients were considered. Presence or absence of first grade diabetic relatives was checked. Patients were administered MYO (1 g/die per os), ALA (400 mg/die per os), MYO (1 gr/die) + ALA (400 mg/die) per os. Only 76 out of 90 patients completed the 12 weeks of treatment. Patients were evaluated before and after the treatment interval for LH, FSH, E2 (estradiol), A (androstenedione), T (testosterone) plasma levels, oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT). All treatments demonstrated specific positive effects: MYO modulated more hormonal profiles and OGTT in polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) with no familial diabetes, ALA improved insulin response to OGTT and metabolic parameters in all patients with no effects on reproductive hormones, MYO + ALA improved hormonal and metabolic aspects and insulin response to OGTT in all patients. Presence of familial diabetes is a relevant clinical aspect. MYO is less effective when familial diabetes is present, ALA improved only metabolic aspects while MYO + ALA was effective on all PCOS patients independently from familial diabetes.
